definitions.definition: ( transitive ) To commit ( official papers ) to some office.
( transitive ) (of a journalist) To submit (an article ) to a newspaper or similar publication.
examples: I filed my copy soon after the interview.

definitions.definition: ( transitive ) To place in an archive in a logical place and order.
examples: Troves of documents filed away in the depository.

definitions.definition: ( transitive ) To store a file ( aggregation of data ) on a storage medium such as a disc or another computer.
( intransitive , with for , chiefly law ) To submit a formal request to some office.
examples: She filed for divorce the next day.
The company filed for bankruptcy when the office opened on Monday.
They filed for a refund under their warranty.

definitions.definition: ( transitive , obsolete ) To set in order; to arrange, or lay away.

definitions.definition: ( intransitive ) To move in a file.
examples: The applicants kept filing into the room until it was full.

main_definition: ( intransitive ) To move in a file.

definitions.definition: ( transitive ) To smooth , grind , or cut with a file.
examples: I'd better file the bottoms of the table legs. Otherwise they will scratch the flooring.

main_definition: ( transitive ) To smooth , grind , or cut with a file.
